# Architecture Rules

Organize code by business domains.

GOOD

audit/

verification/

reports/

payments/

upload/

BAD

controllers/

services/

helpers/

misc/

---

Never duplicate business logic.

Business logic belongs inside domain modules.

UI should remain thin.

---

# AI Rules

AI is NOT allowed to make financial decisions.

AI may only perform:

- CSV mapping
- header normalization
- customer matching
- narrative generation
- executive summaries
- recommendations

AI NEVER performs:

- pricing calculations
- ARR calculations
- revenue leakage detection
- confidence calculations
- invoice comparisons

Those MUST remain deterministic.

---

# Verification Engine

The verification engine is the product moat.

Rules must:

- be deterministic
- be reproducible
- produce evidence
- never depend on LLM output

Every rule returns:

Finding

Evidence

Monthly Leakage

Annual Leakage

Confidence

Recommendation

Rule ID

---

# Canonical Data Model

Everything is converted into canonical objects.

Never build logic directly from CSV files.

CSV

↓

Canonical Objects

↓

Verification Engine

↓

Findings

↓

Reports

Future APIs must map into the same canonical model.

---

# Code Style

Prefer:

small files

pure functions

explicit types

descriptive names

composition over inheritance

Avoid:

large classes

magic values

global state

nested conditionals

---

# Type Safety

No "any"

No ignored TypeScript errors

No ignored Python typing unless unavoidable

Always prefer explicit types.

---

# UI Rules

Always follow the Design System.

Never invent colors.

Never invent spacing.

Never invent typography.

Use design tokens only.

---

Animations:

short

subtle

purposeful

---

Whitespace is preferred over visual clutter.

---

# Components

Prefer reusable components.

If repeated twice,

extract.

If repeated three times,

must extract.

---

# Error Handling

Never silently fail.

Every async operation requires:

loading state

error state

retry state

empty state

---

# Security

Never hardcode:

API keys

tokens

passwords

connection strings

Use environment variables only.

Never expose secrets to frontend.

---

# CSV Processing

Uploads are temporary.

Raw CSV files are deleted after processing.

Business logic never depends on original CSV filenames.

Only canonical data is processed.

---

# Database

Always use migrations.

Never modify production schema manually.

Use foreign keys.

Use indexes where appropriate.

Never duplicate data unnecessarily.

---

# Performance

Prefer server-side processing.

Minimize unnecessary API calls.

Avoid N+1 queries.

Process CSVs in batches when possible.

---

# Testing

Every feature should include:

happy path

error path

edge cases

Validation logic must be tested.

Verification rules must have deterministic tests.

---

# Git

Implement one feature at a time.

Keep commits focused.

Never refactor unrelated code.

---

# Definition of Complete

A feature is complete only when:

✓ Backend implemented

✓ Frontend implemented

✓ Types complete

✓ Validation complete

✓ Loading state exists

✓ Error state exists

✓ Empty state exists

✓ Responsive

✓ Tested

✓ No lint errors

✓ No TODOs

---

# When Unsure

Never guess.

Search the project documentation first.

Reuse existing components.

Keep architecture consistent.

If multiple approaches exist:

Choose the simpler one.

Explain the tradeoff in comments only if necessary.

---

# Priority Order

1. Correctness

2. Evidence quality

3. Simplicity

4. Performance

5. Polish

Never sacrifice correctness for speed.

---

# Working Style

Implement complete vertical slices.

Preferred workflow:

UI

↓

API

↓

Business Logic

↓

Database

↓

Testing

↓

Polish

Do not scaffold dozens of unfinished features.

Each completed feature should be usable before starting the next.

---

# Product Goal

Every decision should move toward one outcome:

A finance leader uploads billing CSVs, receives a trustworthy revenue leakage analysis in minutes, and is confident enough in the evidence to pay for the detailed report.

If a feature does not directly improve that outcome, question whether it belongs in the MVP.